					<div class="post">
				<h3>Re: So far...</h3>
				<div class="date">Posted: <strong>Tue Apr 28, 2020 12:05 am</strong></div>
				<div class="author">by <strong>justine</strong></div>
				<div class="content">Okay,<br>
<br>
So regarding the C10 cap, yeah programming via the USB port <em class="text-italics">should</em> work but I never seem to have luck with this on any of my homespun boards, which you now are all subjected too. Hence the statement about needing the ISP. Maybe I'm doing something consistently boneheaded with the bootloader. Anyway I find it to be so much easier to use an ISP than the USB port as one doesn't need to disrupt the USB/serial connection (which might be open for debugging) just to flash the board, so I don't feel terrible about calling it required hardware.<br>
<br>
Simon, you said you don't have the 6-pin cable. I'm surprised, did the programmer not come with it? The AVR-ISP-Mk2 comes with it, no? By the way an odd thing about that programmer is that the 6-pin cable gets connected to the Mk2's 10-pin header via an adapter, which also should come with it. I've been burned by that because for a while I would do something like drop the programmer, and the cable would come out, and I would put the cable back into the 6-pin header (which seems like the obvious thing to do), and then it seems like dropping the programmer broke it. I think I threw a perfectly good one away once for this reason.<br>
<br>
Re. the ePaper, Simon, did you attach it before integrating the main board with the enclosure, before flexing the display at all?<br>
<br>
I *sincerely* doubt you could have blown the board by soldering it. Are you happy with your solder work? If you want you could post some close-up pictures of the vicinity of the ePaper friend and of the speaker, on the other side, maybe we could comment.</div>
